issue.title: fix(sql): fix comparing Date columns with date literals
issue.body:
Consider this query: `select * from tab where date = '1970-01-01'`

Without these new functions QuestDB resorts to picking the overloaded equal function which accepts 2 longs. Why?
1. There is no exact match for eq(Date, Date) - such function does not exist at all!
2. The date column is `DateColumn` and the Date type can be casted to Long.
   See the overloading priority: /* 7  DATE      */, {DATE, TIMESTAMP, LONG}
3. The second parameter is `StrConstant` and String can be also casted to Long.
   Again, the overloading priority:  /* 11 STRING    */, {STRING, CHAR, DOUBLE, LONG, INT, FLOAT, SHORT, BYTE}
4. Hence, the function parser picks eq(Long, Long).

But then the `StrFunction.getLong()` fails to parse '1970-01-01' as a long. It expects a simple number. It does not know it's supposed to treat the argument as a Date.

The same query works if you change the column type from Date to Timestamp. Why? Timestamp does not rely on casting - it implements Timestamp-specific functions where necessary. So I copied this for Date.

issue.title: feat(sql): moving avg window function
issue.body:
Done so far:

- window size SQL syntax parser and tests for 
```
{ ROWS | RANGE | GROUP }
{ BETWEEN
    { UNBOUNDED PRECEDING
    | CURRENT ROW
    | value_expr [time_unit] { PRECEDING | FOLLOWING }
    }
    AND
    { UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING
    | CURRENT ROW
    | value_expr [time_unit] { PRECEDING | FOLLOWING }
    }
| { UNBOUNDED PRECEDING
  | CURRENT ROW
  | value_expr [time_unit] PRECEDING
  }
}
[ EXCLUDE CURRENT ROW
| EXCLUDE GROUP
| EXCLUDE TIES
| EXCLUDE NO OTHERS
]

where time_unit is allowed  for RANGE frame and is one of: 
- microsecond[s]
- millisecond[s]
- second[s]
- minute[s]
- hour[s]
- day[s]
e.g. 
avg(x) over (partition by y order by ts rows between 10 milliseconds preceding and 10 microseconds preceding)
Time unit is not obligatory and defaults to microseconds, e.g.  
e.g. avg(x) over (partition by y order by ts rows between 10  preceding and 1 preceding)

- implementation of avg() for ROWS frame
   - with / without PARTITION 
   - with / without ORDER BY 
   - with frame_start : UNBOUNDED | X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW
   - with frame_end: X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW, UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING (only if frame_start is UNBOUNDED PRECEDING)
   - exclusion mode:  EXCLUDE NO OTHERS | EXCLUDE CURRENT ROW     
- implementation of avg() for RANGE frame
   - with / without PARTITION 
   - with / without ORDER BY (the latter is only allowed when using default frame) , only order by designated timestamp [ASC | DESC] is allowed 
   - with frame_start : UNBOUNDED | X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW
   - with frame_end: X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW, UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING (only if frame_start is UNBOUNDED PRECEDING, same as with rows frame)
   - exclusion mode:  EXCLUDE NO OTHERS | EXCLUDE CURRENT ROW 
   - unlike in specification, RANGE frame stops at current row and doesn't extend until last row with equal order by column value
   
- implementation skips order by designated_timestamp ASC | DESC in over clause if it matches that of base query
- also fixed issue with analytic factory over base query with order by 
- GROUPS frame is not implemented because it's more readable to use RANGE, considering that order by clause is limited to designated timestamp. 

```

Modelled after https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-expressions.html#SYNTAX-WINDOW-FUNCTIONS

issue.title: feat(sql): moving avg window function
issue.body:
Done so far:

- window size SQL syntax parser and tests for 
```
{ ROWS | RANGE | GROUP }
{ BETWEEN
    { UNBOUNDED PRECEDING
    | CURRENT ROW
    | value_expr [time_unit] { PRECEDING | FOLLOWING }
    }
    AND
    { UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING
    | CURRENT ROW
    | value_expr [time_unit] { PRECEDING | FOLLOWING }
    }
| { UNBOUNDED PRECEDING
  | CURRENT ROW
  | value_expr [time_unit] PRECEDING
  }
}
[ EXCLUDE CURRENT ROW
| EXCLUDE GROUP
| EXCLUDE TIES
| EXCLUDE NO OTHERS
]

where time_unit is allowed for RANGE frame and is one of: 
- microsecond
- millisecond
- second
- minute
- hour
- day

- implementation of avg() for ROWS frame
   - with / without PARTITION 
   - with / without ORDER BY 
   - with frame_start : UNBOUNDED | X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW
   - with frame_end: X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW, UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING (only if frame_start is UNBOUNDED PRECEDING)
   - exclusion mode:  EXCLUDE NO OTHERS | EXCLUDE CURRENT ROW

- implementation of avg() for RANGE frame
   - with / without PARTITION 
   - with / without ORDER BY (the latter is only allowed when using default frame) , only order by designated timestamp [ASC | DESC] is allowed 
   - with frame_start : UNBOUNDED | X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW
   - with frame_end: X PRECEDING, CURRENT_ROW
   - exclusion mode:  EXCLUDE NO OTHERS | EXCLUDE CURRENT ROW 
   - unlike in specification, RANGE frame stops at current row and doesn't extend until last row with equal order by column value
   - 
- implementation skips order by designated_timestamp ASC | DESC in over clause if it matches that of base query
- also fixed issue with analytic factory over base query with order by 

```

issue.title: fix(sql): fix comparing Date columns with date literals
issue.body:
Consider this query: `select * from tab where date = '1970-01-01'`

Without these new functions QuestDB resorts to picking the overloaded equal function which accepts 2 longs. Why?
1. There is no exact match for eq(Date, Date) - such function does not exist at all!
2. The date column is `DateColumn` and the Date type can be casted to Long.
   See the overloading priority: /* 7  DATE      */, {DATE, TIMESTAMP, LONG}
3. The second parameter is `StrConstant` and String can be also casted to Long.
   Again, the overloading priority:  /* 11 STRING    */, {STRING, CHAR, DOUBLE, LONG, INT, FLOAT, SHORT, BYTE}
4. Hence, the function parser picks eq(Long, Long).

But then the `StrFunction.getLong()` fails to parse '1970-01-01' as a long. It expects a simple number. It does not know it's supposed to treat the argument as a Date.

The same query works if you change the column type from Date to Timestamp. Why? Timestamp does not rely on casting - it implements Timestamp-specific functions where necessary. So I copied this for Date.


TODO: 
- Tests
- More Date functions?

issue.title: fix(sql): fix comparing Date columns with date literals
issue.body:
Consider this query: `select * from tab where date = '1970-01-01'`

Without these new functions QuestDB resorts to picking the overloaded equal function which accepts 2 longs. Why?
1. There is no exact match for eq(Date, Date) - such function does not exist at all!
2. The date column is `DateColumn` and the Date type can be casted to Long.
   See the overloading priority: /* 7  DATE      */, {DATE, TIMESTAMP, LONG}
3. The second parameter is `StrConstant` and String can be also casted to Long.
   Again, the overloading priority:  /* 11 STRING    */, {STRING, CHAR, DOUBLE, LONG, INT, FLOAT, SHORT, BYTE}
4. Hence, the function parser picks eq(Long, Long).

But then the `StrFunction.getLong()` fails to parse '1970-01-01' as a long. It expects a simple number. It does not know it's supposed to treat the argument as a Date.

The same query works if you change the column type from Date to Timestamp. Why? Timestamp does not rely on casting - it implements Timestamp-specific functions where necessary. So I copied this for Date.


TODO: 
- Tests
- More Date functions?

@bluestreak01: I tried the experiment we discussed the other day: I introduced `EqDateStringFunctionFactory` with this signature: `=(Ms)` and reverted the functional changes inside `FunctionParser`. However, this had unexpected side effects. 

Consider this table: `create table tab (ts timestamp);`  and this SQL: `select * from tab where ts = '2022-01-01'` This is supposed to match the `EqTimestampFunctionFactory`. However, it started to match the `EqDateStringFunctionFactory` instead! Because the 2nd argument matched exactly (string constant) and the `Timestamp` column can be cast to `Date`. This is not undesirable, we do not want to cast Timestamp to a coarse-grained Date for no good reason. Thus I think the tiny change in `FunctionParser` is safer.

issue.title: chore(core): split Utf8Sequence hierarchy from UTF-16 specific CharSequence

labels.name: Core
labels.description: Related to storage, data type, etc.

issue.body:
Involves a number of changes aimed to get rid of `CharSequence` classes that we storing UTF-8 bytes as `char`s.

Namely, includes the following changes:
* Introduces a new hierarchy of `Utf8Sequence` and `Utf8Sink` based classes. These classes are aimed to represent and accumulate UTF-8 string bytes. The main difference between the sink classes is `put()` method behavior - the new sinks handle UTF-16 strings correctly instead of doing the `(byte) seq.charAt(i)` downcast. The old ASCII-only behavior is exposed via the `putAscii()` method.
* Migrates all UTF-8 sinks to be based on the `Utf8Sink` interface and friends.
* Introduces `Utf8*Map` classes as a replacement to `ByteChar*Map`. All `*ByteChar*` classes are gone.
* `Utf8s` utility now holds a bunch of UTF-8 and UTF-8<->UTF-16 conversion methods. Certain methods suffixed with `*Ascii` are aimed to simplify ASCII-only code (otherwise, we'd have to introduce quite some `Utf8String` constants here and there). `Utf8Sequence#asAsciiCharSequence()` method is exposed for those rare cases when it's not worth it to rewrite ASCII `CharSequence` specific code to also accept a `Utf8Sequence`.
* A few minor code enhancements here and there.

As a rule of thumb, whenever the string was received or has to be sent over the wire/stdin/stdout/etc., it's UTF-8, so `CharSequence` and `CharSink` shouldn't be involved. If you see such a case remaining somewhere, it should be migrated to the new UTF-8 interfaces.

issue.title: chore(core): split Utf8Sequence hierarchy from UTF-16 specific CharSequence

labels.name: Core
labels.description: Related to storage, data type, etc.

issue.body:
Involves a number of changes aimed to get rid of `CharSequence` classes that we storing UTF-8 bytes as `char`s.

Namely, includes the following changes:
* Introduces a new hierarchy of `Utf8Sequence` and `Utf8Sink` based classes. These classes are aimed to represent and accumulate UTF-8 string bytes. The main difference between the sink classes is `put()` method behavior - the new sinks handle UTF-16 strings correctly instead of doing the `(byte) seq.charAt(i)` downcast. The old ASCII-only behavior is exposed via the `putAscii()` method.
* Migrates all UTF-8 sinks to be based on the `Utf8Sink` interface and friends.
* Introduces `Utf8*Map` classes as a replacement to `ByteChar*Map`. All `*ByteChar*` classes are gone.
* `Utf8s` utility now holds a bunch of UTF-8 and UTF-8<->UTF-16 conversion methods. Certain methods suffixed with `*Ascii` are aimed to simplify ASCII-only code (otherwise, we'd have to introduce quite some `Utf8String` constants here and there). `Utf8Sequence#asAsciiCharSequence()` method is exposed for those rare cases when it's not worth it to rewrite ASCII `CharSequence` specific code to also accept a `Utf8Sequence`.
* A few minor code enhancements here and there.

As a rule of thumb, whenever the string was received or has to be sent over the wire/stdin/stdout/etc., it's UTF-8, so `CharSequence` and `CharSink` shouldn't be involved. If you see such a case remaining somewhere, it should be migrated to the new UTF-8 interfaces.
